                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d426">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94 Commission/643: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan (<persName
                            corresp="frus1932v03#p_GJC1" type="from">Grew</persName>) to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-12-13T17:00:00+09:00"
                            >December 13, 1932—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 13—6:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>279. The British Ambassador, under instructions from his Government, yesterday
                    urged <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_UCY1">Count Uchida</persName> to agree to
                    the organization of a conciliation commission for settlement of the
                    Sino-Japanese issue regarding Manchuria, adding that unless this were done it
                    would be necessary for the League of Nations to proceed under the provisions of
                    paragraph 4 of article 15 of the Covenant. <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_LSF1">Lindley</persName> tells me that his
                    representations contained no hint of a threat as indicated in press despatches
                    and that they conveyed merely a statement of fact regarding normal League
                    procedure. <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_UCY1">Count Uchida</persName> said
                    that he could give no decision until he had further studied the matter. He
                    thought it would be easier to approve of the proposed commission of conciliation
                    if it were entirely separated from the League and made an independent body.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_GJC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
